1 Introduction

Median is middle point of sample. When we measure median from a ramdom sample, since we do not know the underlying data distribution, there is uncertainty of median. We want to find out which quantiles of a continous distribution gives more precision.

median: g(X1,X2,…,XN)=smallest x such that 1N∑i=1NI(Xi≤x)=.5 The kth order statistic in a statistical sample is the kth-smallest value. density pdf QQ plot

Add a longer introduction and background about assignment. Add in written explanations for all outputs. I need to know what you learned from the graphs and functions at each step. Code for first 6 graphs is correct. # Background

Continous random varibel has continuum of points in a range. Continuous probability model means all interval of equal length have the same likelihood.

The density functions to continuous random variable is like probability mass function to discrete random variables. CDF can be used to learn about probability of continuous random variable. Steeper interval means the random variable will take values more frequently than flatter interval. Derivative of the cdf, is probability density function. PDF depicts the relative likelihood, high density region means the random variable will take values more frequently than lower density interval.

2 Questions

2.0.1 Q: Begin with the median from a sample of N = 200 from the standard normal distribution. Write an R function that is the density function for the median in this sample. Note that the 100th order statistic is approximately the median, and use the order statistic formula discussed in class. Generate a plot of the function.

dorder <- function(x, k, n){
  k*choose(n,k)*
    (pnorm(x,0,1))^(k-1)*
    (1-pnorm(x,0,1))^(n-k)*
    dnorm(x,0,1)
}

curve(dorder(x, 100, 200), -0.5,0.5, ylab="Density")

Between -0.2 and 0.2 has the highest density, in a sample of 200, the median (100th) will occur most frequently in range of (-0.2, 0.2).

2.0.2 Q: Write an R function that is the probability function for the median in this sample. Use the order statistic formula discussed in class. Generate a plot of the function.

porder <- function(x){
  pbinom(100-1, 200, pnorm(x), lower.tail = FALSE)
}

curve(porder(x),-0.5,0.5, ylab = "Probability")

2.0.3 Q: Write an R function that is the quantile function for the median in this sample. (You have several options for how to write this function.) Generate a plot of the function.

qorder <- function(p){
  out <- p
  for (i in seq_along(p)){
    out[i] <- uniroot(function(x){porder(x)-p[i]},c(-100,100))$root
  }
  out
}
p<- seq(0.05,0.95,by =0.01)
plot(p, qorder(p), type="l", ylim=c(-2,2))
lines(p, qnorm(p),col="steelblue",lwd=3)

  pbinom(k-1, n, pnorm(x), lower.tail = FALSE)

  out<-p

### Q: Modify the dorder, porder, and qorder functions so that the functions take new parameters dist and … so that the functions will work for any continuous distribution that has d and p functions defined in R.

newdorder <- function(x,k,n,dist="norm",...){
  pf <- get(paste0("p",dist))
  df <- get(paste0("d",dist))
   k*
    choose(n, k)*
    pf(x, ...)^(k-1)*
    (1-pf(x, ...))^(n-k)*
    df(x, ...)
}
newporder <- function(x, k, n, dist = "norm", ...){
  pf <- get(paste0("p", dist))
  pbinom(k-1, n, pf(x, ...), lower.tail = FALSE)
}
newqorder <- function(p, k, n, dist = "norm", ...){
  out <- p
  for(i in seq_along(p)){
    out[i] <- uniroot(function(x){porder(x, k, n, dist, ...) - p[i]}, c(-100,100))$root
  }
  out
}

2.0.9 Q: Use the newly modified functions to plot the probability and density functions for the sample min (N = 200).

curve(
  newdorder(x, 1, 200, dist = "norm")
  , xlim = c(-5, -1)
  , ylab = "Density"
  , main = "Density of Minimum for Normal Distribution)"
)

curve(
  newporder(x, 1, 200, dist = "norm")
  , xlim = c(-5, -1)
  , ylab = "Probability"
  , main = "Density of Minimum for Normal Distribution"
)

From density and probability function, the minimum in a sample of 200 will most likely be between -4 and -2.
